  <mn>3</mn>\n          </mtd>\n        </mtr>\n        <mtr>\n          <mtd>\n            <mn>4</mn>\n          </mtd>\n          <mtd>\n            <mrow>\n              <mn>12</mn>\n            </mrow>\n          </mtd>\n        </mtr>\n      </mtable>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em>&nbsp;<em><strong>(C4)</strong></em></p>\n<p class=\"accept\"><strong>Note:</strong> Correct solution with inversion (ie <em>AB</em> instead of <em>BA</em>) earns FT marks, (maximum <em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em>).</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"10004","referenceCode":"EXM.1.AHL.TZ0.3","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"A and B are 2 × 2 matrices, where A = [ 5 2 2 0 ] and B A = [ 11 2 44 8 ] . Find B","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"3","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.14—Introduction to matrices"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}